MEASLES - CANADA (03): (BRITISH COLUMBIA), USA (WASHINGTON) ALERT
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1] Canada (BC)
Date: Fri 16 Apr 2010
Source: Bclocalnews.com [edited]
<http://www.bclocalnews.com/news/91071064.html>


Another 14 cases of measles have been confirmed in the Lower Mainland that
are linked to an outbreak that began in March [2010]. As of 15 Apr 2010, a
total of 44 cases have been reported across British Columbia [BC], with 7
new [cases] in both the Fraser and Vancouver Coastal health regions.

"We're seeing a lot of cases in people who are either unimmunized or they
have an unknown immunization history," said Ritinder Harry, spokesperson
for the BC Centre for Disease Control. A total of 17 people in Fraser
Health have now tested positive for measles, plus 17 more in Vancouver
Coastal. There are usually very few, if any, cases of measles in BC.

But the refusal of some people to have their children vaccinated is making
pockets of the population more vulnerable to diseases that were thought to
have been virtually eradicated in North America.

Ritinder Harry is reminding people to vaccinate their children against
measles at age one year and 18 months. She said adults not sure about their
own status should check their immunization records. One Vancouver school
has sent unvaccinated students home for 3 weeks after several students
there came down with measles. The measles outbreak is thought to have
arrived here with at least 2 foreign visitors during the Olympics.

The illness causes fever, runny nose, and a cough. A rash develops later,
often accompanied by sore, red eyes and light sensitivity. It may also
cause ear infections, pneumonia and, in rare cases, encephalitis, deafness,
brain damage or death.

There are also 7 reported cases in the interior, 2 in the north and one on
Vancouver Island.

[byline: Jeff Nagel]

