******
[2] USA (WA)
Date: Fri 16 Apr 2010
From: Seatlepi blogs [edited]
<http://blog.seattlepi.com/thebigblog/archives/202205.asp>


King County health officials are warning that a woman who has measles
visited Seattle earlier this month [April 2010]. The woman was visiting
from British Columbia, where there have been 44 confirmed measles cases.
The woman was at the Seattle Aquarium from 3 to 7 pm on 3 Apr 2010.

The risk may be low here because many are vaccinated against the disease.
Those born before 1957 probably had the disease. But people who aren't
vaccinated are at high risk, and that includes children who are one or
younger. They are too young to be vaccinated. Pregnant women and people
with weakened immune systems are at risk even if they have been vaccinated.
If you are in this group and develop an illness with fever or unexplained
rash, call your doctor.

Health officials said people who might have [contracted] measles in this
case would be expected to develop a rash between 10 and 24 Apr 2010.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[This importation of measles virus infection into British Columbia around
the time of the Winter Olympics in Vancouver is continuing to reveal
susceptible members of the community who are unprotected by prior vaccination.

A British Columbian resident visiting Seattle has triggered an alert in
neighbouring Washington state, but no transmission of measles virus
infection has been recorded so far.

A map of British Columbia showing the location Vancouver can be accessed
at: <http://www.britishcolumbia.com/Maps/?id=2>. The HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map of Canada is available at: <http://healthmap.org/r/007x>. -
Mod.CP]
